Part 2.7: At the bottom of the ocean (there are treasures)

At eleven, Arthur had been taken off his ancestral grounds without knowing that he would never once again set foot onto the home of his birth.

At fourteen, Arthur had become one of the youngest Empress Consorts in history. 

At fifteen, the same begetter found himself subjugated to a life of slavery.

The branding must be the most awful moment of his life. The way red hot iron seared his flesh, melting layers of skin and fat and burning the muscles below his collarbone as he trashed in pain – pain, so much pain clouding his senses, his nerves on fire –his arms and legs pinned under iron cuffs on the ground, the cold, thick metal chafing his skin. He didn’t believe that that animalistic, blood-curdling scream filling the dungeon was spilled out of his own mouth until his throat hurt when he attempted to stop his saliva from leaking off his lips. Arthur could literally smell his own burnt flesh, and it made him sick. Fortunately, there was only bile when he vomited on the floor next to his head, otherwise the stench would have triggered his gag reflex again. As it was, Arthur passed out from the pain soon after he was branded.

The other slaves and servants were kind enough to clothe him in garbs with low collars. His mark of ownership was exposed for everyone to see, sure, but at least there was no layer of fabric irritating his raw, sensitive wound. Anyways, the sooner it dried the better.

Ironically, his first noteworthy ‘task’ was to safely transport the Cornflower, the Carnation and Princess Maria out of the Capital.

They’d approached him in the dark of the night a few days after the fever that signaled his infection from the branding cooled down. The Edelweiss had been keeping contact with him as he fed him medicine secretly. When asked, Arthur admitted that he was familiar with the ways of the underground water tunnels in the Capital (don’t ask how or why) so he was in.

“You won’t believe the nerve of that old geezer,” the Carnation sighed as Arthur helped him pack the handiest of clothing for every season into his luggage in silence. His young daughter was asleep at the other end of his chamber. “As soon as he’s Regent, he started replacing the Ministers in the parliament with his own people! And there have been mysterious disappearances of those who opposed him. Soon enough, he’ll be sending people to assassinate us,” he frowned. 

“That’s why we’re getting away before he can,” the Cornflower threw a cloak at the Carnation’s face. “Less talking and more packing!” He placed his hands at the sides of his heavily pregnant waist. He looked so full, like he was about to give birth any time. Arthur eyed his abdomen warily, concerned about his state.

The Cornflower noticed Arthur’s stare and merely grinned wryly. “We have no choice,” he shook his head, “better leave now with the baby inside of me. It’s harder to watch out for his people once he or she is out of my body. The awesome me will be fine, brat!”

Instead of rolling his eyes (like he used to do), Arthur merely bit his lower lip and busied himself with packing.

“…Hey,” the Cornflower nudged his former student on the shoulder with one hand, the other hand digging deep into the recess of his pocket. Arthur blinked as he procured a golden necklace with small chips of blue and red gems attached to the delicate chain, and deposited the jewelry to his hand.

“When you need money for yourself, sell it,” the Cornflower grinned at him when Arthur looked at him in puzzlement. “My House’s emblem is cast on this plate, here,” the albino pointed at the metal near one of the beads, “so that if anybody tries to raise a fuss by claiming that you stole it from them, you can tell him I gave this to you.”

Arthur raised his brow as the Edelweiss snorted. “Won’t that sound suspicious after you’re missing?” Well said, Edelweiss, Arthur thought. The Cornflower often meant well, but he was…sometimes mentally challenged.

“Err…” the Cornflower blinked before his cheeks turned red. “Shaddup! Anyways, sell this the first chance you get! The money will certainly do you some good!” he huffed.

Arthur accepted the necklace with his palms and smiled. “Thank you.”

Everyone paused and stared.

Arthur blinked. “W-what?”

The Cornflower ruffled his hair. “It’s good that you can still smile,” he, too, had a smile on his face. None of his badass grin – just a soft, simple smile. “Listen, brat, the key to surviving in the Castle is to stay low. And stick to Alfie. He can and he will protect you.”

“I know…” Arthur looked down at the floor, “but…I don’t want to bother him.”

“Seriously? Alfie would cry a flood without you. That kid needs you!” The albino raised his voice.

Everyone shushed him and peered at the Princess in the bed. She was still blissfully asleep.

“Think of it this way,” the Edelweiss continued in hushed tones, “You’re the only parental figure Their Highnesses have left, because the only thing Duke Orleans is interested in is how he can manipulate his grandsons to do his biddings. The Princes will play their part, and you should play yours too.”

“Well said!” The Cornflower slapped the Edelweiss’ back and the brunet scowled. “By the way, little master, where will you be going?” he asked casually.

The Edelweiss was neither pregnant nor with a child. Arthur thought (hoped) he was going to stay.

“To my father’s home, most likely,” the bespectacled musician sighed. “I have no wish to serve Duke Orleans or be involved in his politics. I’d rather retreat away from the Capital. I imagine the court will be a circus under his…reign.” He turned to Arthur and his lips curled downward. “I’m sorry.”

Arthur shook his head. “No such thing,” he mumbled, “everyone should take care of himself now.”

The Carnation snapped the lid of his luggage with a resounding ‘click’ that carried a sense of finality. The four widows looked at each other for a long time, memorizing each other’s features, before the Edelweiss ended the strange moment of connection by clearing his throat. “Well…”

The Carnation picked up his (still slumbering) daughter into his arms, while Arthur picked up their luggage. “Let’s go!” The Carnation grinned.

They departed.

(Every slave and servant was heavily punished after the disappearance of two prominent former flowers and one (and a half) heir to the throne was discovered. But nobody could track it back to him. The Edelweiss had covered their tracks well. Arthur kept an ear for any news of them and breathed a sigh of relief after weeks of no news. When it was time for the Edelweiss to depart, Arthur still shed a tear no matter how much he’d steeled his heart.)

----------

“Arthur!”

Prince Alfred launched himself into Arthur’s arms the moment the slave entered his room to change the linens. Apparently, the chief had made him in charge of cleaning the Princes’ chambers after the Princes (or rather, Prince Alfred) stirred up a ruckus. Still, one week had passed from the day Arthur owed his life to the young blue-eyed blonde.

“Where have you been?” Prince Alfred sighed as he nuzzled the older man’s side, small arms holding his waist tightly. “I’ve been so scared for you…”

Arthur placed his hand on the Prince’s shoulders awkwardly, his fingertips giving the royalty the barest of touch. “I’m sorry to have worried you, Your Highness.”

The Prince withdrew from him and glared. “Arthur,” he frowned, “call me like you used to.”

“Prince Alfred,” Arthur kneeled in front of his charge to bring their eyes level, “things have changed. I’m no longer in a position that allows me to touch you and address you casually.”

“As long as we’re alone, it should be okay, right?” Prince Alfred’s lips turned downward. “Arthur-”

“Excuse me…” the door to the room creaked open, and Arthur nearly jumped away from the Prince before Prince Matthew’s head poked into the room. “I heard Arthur’s here…” he slipped into the small gap between the door and the frame and shuffled his feet.

“Prince Matthew,” Arthur allowed the shy Prince a smile. “Your humble subject is here.” He gave him a quick bow.

Though the quiet monarch looked bothered by his former tutor’s greeting, he approached him steadily and offered a bundle of paper to his face. “…You’ve lost weight,” his thin brows creased, “I’ve brought some food for you…I hope…no, I insist you accept it.”

Arthur resisted the urge to blink and let his smile widen instead. Passive aggressiveness suited Prince Matthew, somewhat. “Thank you very much, Your Highness,” Arthur raised his hands to receive the package.

Prince Alfred, who was pouting and glaring at his twin for taking Arthur’s attention off him, suddenly grabbed Arthur’s hands. His skin was filled with angry red burnt marks and hard calluses.  “What happened to them?” Prince Alfred asked worriedly as he pulled one of Arthur’s hands closer to his face and turned his palm.

“Prince Alfred, you needn’t worry,” Arthur reassured the boy as the three of them stared at his bruised and battered hand. “I was merely acquainting myself with a coal iron,” he stated, but when Prince Alfred touched one of the blisters he couldn’t help but jerk and hiss in pain.

“You’re not okay at all!” Prince Alfred’s frown deepened. “I’ll tell the chief to get you off ironing duti-”

“No, I’m really okay,” Arthur insisted. He knew the Edelweiss had told him to let Prince Alfred protect him, but this was really too much, he felt. “Do you remember that a few months ago, when you started learning sword fighting, your palm started to hurt?” Arthur moved his finger across the raised, hardened calluses on the young Prince’s palm. Almost immediately, Prince Alfred quieted. Arthur had learned long ago that his young charge tended to behave agreeably when he was showered with affection, and used this finding to get him to at least listen to his views.  “It’s the same with this,” Arthur smiled at him, “give it a few more days, and I’ll be fine.”

Prince Alfred stared at him for a long, long time before his gaze dropped to the mark below Arthur’s collarbone. “…Does it still hurt?” His fingers reached out to caress it, only to halt midair.

“It doesn’t hurt anymore,” Arthur answered honestly.

The Prince sighed. “If you say so…”

When Prince Alfred settled himself on Arthur’s chest, his protests settling onto the silent crease on his brows, Arthur let him be. He sent Prince Matthew, who was eyeing the oldest blonde hesitantly, a welcoming gaze. The smile on the quieter twin’s face when he joined them in a group hug was simply beautiful.

----------

Surprisingly, Arthur settled into the life of a slave fairly well.

He’d been rotated to different parts of the Castle for the chief to find what he was good at performing. He was forbidden from entering the kitchen after barely ten minutes of chopping vegetables and boiling soup, but generally, Arthur loved the stable, the gardens and the laundry room best. He loved taking care of the horses, digging his fingers in dirt as he planted the bulbs or sitting next to the window sill with beddings or curtains for the next balls or celebrations in his hands.

It was probably because the home of his ancestral grounds didn’t employ that many servants. Women didn’t survive very well in northern borderlands, which were riddled with harsh weather, wild animals and threats of disputes with neighbouring states. There weren’t that many farms either, so they grew their own vegetables. Erin was too clumsy with threads and needles so more often than not it was Arthur who accompanied their mother in autumns, stitching the seams of winter coats for four growing children near the fireplace, as James and their father looked for firewood. Rhys liked to insist on the importance of taking care of his horses (and sheep), and the mares he’d nurtured could run faster than the wind and often won races in town. Arthur’d learned a lot from simply lending his quiet brother a hand.

(Reminiscing of his childhood made him miss his family like there was a hole in his chest, so he’d quickly banish the memories from his mind and focus on the chores at hand.)

Some slaves and servants liked to mock him and assign him heavy tasks or beat him up for ‘not moping the floor properly’ (for he was a newbie and therefore, at the bottom of the food chain and boy, did they like reminding him of that), but mostly they ignored him. Some of them treated him amicably, too, for Arthur never reacted to any baiting or kept a distance with anyone. He was unexpectedly calm about the transition over his lifestyle.

His sleeping quarter was a barrack shared with numerous other slaves. His bunk bed was made of rattan and hay (as a newbie, he was relegated to the bottommost surface, where bugs could crawl over him when he slept). He hadn’t been able to sleep well, because during cold, windy nights the draft was terrible.

And the child sleeping next to him had been crying.

She was a small, small girl, aged six at most, with beady dark eyes and shoulder-length inky black hair. Her parents must have been Easterners. She’d quieted after she’d been shushed by the teenage maid sleeping above her, but still sobbed herself to sleep on most nights, occasionally hiccoughing and blowing her nose quietly.

Arthur let her be and minded his own business (there were too many miserable children in slavery for him to care of) until one afternoon, when he was sitting in the laundry room behind a basinful of tablecloth, bubbles and scent of flowery detergent filling the damp room, the section-in-charge - a strict redhead in her mid-twenties with a no-nonsense attitude - barged into the room and shouted, “Who of you idiots washed the crimson curtains of the throne room till the colour fades?”

Arthur distinctly remembered his sleeping neighbour the Eastern kid working on those curtains in the morning (because the cloth was huge and took a long time to scrub). He peeked to the side and there she was (she had mostly the same shifts with him, having entered the Castle not long before Arthur’s life as a slave started), scrubbing another piece of cloth. Her small, short hands were shaking. But the rest of her body wasn’t, and she wasn’t avoiding the section-in-charge’s scrutinizing stare. She wasn’t afraid of the punishment, it seemed (one learned how to accept them with resignation after sometime), but a longer look on her arms revealed that they were marred blue, black and red, dark straight lashes left behind from recent caning still unhealed. That must be the reason for her mistake.

Before the other slaves pointed at her in unison (for everyone would be punished if no one claimed the blame, and children weren’t spared any mercy in slavery), Arthur quickly voiced out. “I deeply apologise, it was my blunder.”

The in-charge pursed her lips at him. “Get out,” she barked.

Arthur caught the kid’s anxious gaze before he exited through the door and sent her what he hoped was a reassuring smile.

Much, much later, when everyone was asleep and Arthur was trying to ignore the stinging of his arms, someone shimmied to his side and draped a makeshift blanket of messily-patched old clothes over him.

“Why did you take the caning for me?” she whispered as she touched his hands softly, beady eyes staring raptly at him like a kitten’s.

“Because you couldn’t possibly withstand anymore with these hands,” he caught her wrist in his significantly larger palm and dropped a kiss to her skin. God, but was he a sucker for kids. “Don’t mind it too much.”

She grew quiet for a while before she finally curled herself into a ball and tucked herself under Arthur’s chin. “I only managed to snatch enough material to patch one blanket,” she whispered in explanation.

“I’m Arthur,” Arthur accepted her gratitude. “What’s your name?” he asked as he petted her hair absently.

“Xin,” the little girl answered as she dozed off. [1]

And that was the start of their relationship.

(His uncovered legs still felt cold, but the warmth of her small body made up for it. After weeks of restless sleep, Arthur finally obtained a piece of respite.)

----------

Arthur liked servicing the nobles the least.

Whenever he swept the floor or changed the beddings of their private chambers, he always executed his tasks with as much efficiency as possible. Sometimes, when he wasn’t fast enough to slink away from the masters of the chambers’ sight, some of the aristocrats (especially Duke Orleans’ men) liked to command him to perform ‘favours’ for them.

“You’re good, huh?” They often said as they used his mouth or…his other body parts. “Did you use these to get the Emperor hooked?”

After these episodes, Arthur often secluded himself near the well at the edge of the Castle, close to the forest, at night, and scrubbed himself till his skin was red and raw even when he was still bruised. He’d shiver, his teeth clacking as he vomited bile and digested chunks of coarse bread onto the ground and still he couldn’t get the foul taste of semen and cum out of his mouth and he felt disgusted, he hated it, he hated himself so much-

Then Xin came to him with warm leftovers from the kitchen (Xin got assigned to kitchen duties way, way more often than Arthur), wiped him dry, treated his wounds and let him cuddle her as they ate together, and life seemed a little better.

----------

(Life seemed most bearable in Spring, when the flowers he'd tended started to bloom, and it didn't hurt to stay in the gardens as long as he could because he wouldn't get sunburns. Cool breezes weaved between his hair and his sweaty neck and Arthur thought he'd found a piece of Heaven on earth.)

----------

“Are you hurt?”

Arthur looked up from the clean clothes he was folding and arranging into the closet to Prince Alfred, who was in his pajama robe, swinging his legs at the edge of his four-poster bed. “…Not particularly,” Arthur pasted a smile on his face.

(Though technically he was in-charge of tending to the Prince’s chamber, Arthur only spent a maximum of six hours per week here, most of which the owner was out studying with his (new) tutors. The master of the chamber had taken to skipping classes to wait for him on several occasions, and it took some negotiating with the chief to fix Arthur’s schedule in such a way that he would clean Prince Alfred’s rooms when the monarch was actually inside.)

Prince Alfred frowned. “But you’ve been limping.”

Arthur’s heart lodged itself in his throat. For a moment, the only thing he could feel was fear and oh no he knows now before his heartbeat slowed down again. “…I tripped over the stairs when I was cleaning the railings,” he finally managed to say.

Prince Alfred’s sky blue eyes stared into his eyes in a piercing gaze. “…Liar,” he hissed vehemently.

“Prince Alf-”

“Somebody hurt you, right?” The boy (almost ten years old now, and shooting up like a stalk, lean muscles from sword fighting and physical exercises with the Empire’s best veterans and teachers filling his limbs and torso. Arthur already knew Prince Alfred would grow up to be bigger than him, bigger than his own father, even) rose to his feet and approached the slave with sure, steady steps. “Tell me who did it!”

“Please, calm down,” Arthur rose to his feet, too, and moved his hands in a pacifying gesture. “Nobody hurt me. I just tripped.”

“…do you seriously think I would believe your lie?” the Prince took a deep breath and stopped in front of the older blonde, hurt clouding his expression. “…you know that you can count on me to protect you, right?” he placed his hands on the thinner man’s shoulders, blue eyes merely inches lower from Arthur’s.

“…Of course I do,” Arthur replied, and he believed what he said. “It’s just…” you will think I’m disgusting you’ll hate me you won’t understand, “…I was clumsy enough to make mistakes and so I was punished. It’s as simple as that. I can handle it on my own. You can’t be giving me special treatments all the time. What would the nobles feel if they see the Crown Prince just devoting his time to worrying about just one slave? They may be working for you as your ministers or administrators in the future, you know,” he spoke calmly. For one moment, Arthur felt like he was still the Prince’s tutor, advising the boy on how to deal with politics in his court.

You don’t get it, Prince Alfred thought and frowned. You’re still trying to protect me. “I’m fine,” he insisted, “I can handle them on my own too!”

“So let us handle our issues on our own, then,” Arthur latched on to the Prince’s own words, and the boy seethed when he realised he’d been led. “Arthur!” his pitch rose.

“Your Highness,” Arthur placed his hands over Prince Alfred’s hands and rubbed them soothingly, “Trust and respect has to be earned. To be the best ruler for your Empire, you should focus on building your knowledge and your relationships with the nobles, do you understand?” He offered the boy a soft smile.

You’re not ‘just one slave’, the Prince protested inwardly, but he conceded (for now) and laid his head on Arthur’s shoulder and enveloped his (thin) frame in his arms. Expectedly, Arthur allowed the embrace.

On hindsight, Arthur should have been sensitive enough to recognize that utilizing touches to keep the boy’s temper and stubbornness in check would yield repercussions, but he didn’t stop.

And the repercussions continued to grow.

TBC

Note:1. Xin is my OC, Singapore (Xin-Jia-Bo). She’ll grow to be Arthur’s most loyal lady-in-waiting, his eyes and ears in the Castle.

Part 2.5: Fallen

 

Arthur had trained under the Cornflower’s guidance for at least two years, after which the flower declared that he had nothing more to impart to his disciple.

From the looks of it, the Cornflower didn’t lie.

The duel was challenging. The two of them knew each other’s moves too well for any to wedge in any advantage through element of surprise. Arthur circled his former tutor warily, eyeing the bump on his stomach as he dodged blows upon blows.

“Brat!” Arthur narrowly avoided a thrust aimed at his shoulder, “Just because you’ve been given the title of a flower, and you’ve won Francis’ favour, you think you own the court? Don’t be so cocky!” Crimson eyes bore into his skull. “I swear I’ll make you learn your place!”

The Cornflower bent forward to an all too familiar stance, his right arm level against his cheek and the length of his left hand accompanying his blade, two fingers pressed on the flat of the pointy edge of his sword. Arthur gulped nervously and brought the length of his sword across his torso in a protective gesture. He’d seen this technique many times and he’d never managed to block it.

Green eyes met red, and Arthur took a deep breath.

The Cornflower winked. And lurched forward.

Arthur blinked in puzzlement and nearly missed the slightly inaccurate angle of the tilt of the Cornflower’s torso, the sheer deliberateness of the mistake (to those who knew him well enough, which was to say, less than a handful of the nobles in the huge ballroom). He took half a step to the right, letting the former general sail past him, hit his hand with the blunt edge of the hilt of his sword and knocked the Cornflower down through an elbow to his back.

The Cornflower’s sword fell to the floor with a loud clanging noise, and skittered to the crowd, who jerked away in surprise.

Arthur stared at the fallen weapon numbly, disbelieving that the tensest ten minutes of his life (yet) was over, before he snapped into awareness at the groan that escaped the Cornflower’s lips as he rubbed his spine from his position on the floor. Arthur scrambled to approach his former tutor, his sword cast aside thoughtlessly, before crouching down next to him and offering his hand. “Are you all right? I’m so sorry!”

“Runt,” the former warmonger stared at him for a moment, his crimson gaze imploring, before he smirked and accepted the hand which had been offered to him, the line of his lips peaceful and acquiescent. He swept back the white strands of hair that were plastered to his forehead, the aquamarine and diamonds of the cornflower attached to his hair gleaming under the lights of the chandelier in the ballroom, before he grinned. “You’re surprisingly talented, aren’t ya?” The statement was followed by a thorough glomping.”Welcome to the court!”

The cloak of silence persisted. Not even a breathy whisper could be heard, until two sets of footsteps echoed loudly in the spacious ballroom. Arthur nearly jumped in shock when gloved hands were placed casually on his shoulder and on his back. He looked up to find the Edelweiss and the Carnation flanking his sides, decked in ivory, maroon, lavender and gold, regal colours of their Houses. “It’s my greatest loss,” Lord Carriedo sighed heartily. Arthur eyed him warily. Since entering the court, he’d had the feeling Lord Carriedo disliked him. “The Rose has been taking care of my little querida so well. There’s no one else I trust with this position.” The brunette squeezed the blonde’s shoulder and smiled.

When Arthur blinked at the older flower in surprise, the Edelweiss and the Cornflower obtained a flute of champagne each and raised them to the air. “To Empress Consort Rose,” the musician’s tenor was clear as a bell, unhesitant and authoritative. The Carnation and the Cornflower followed suit.

The crowd stared at each other, waiting, searching for cues. Arthur waited with bated breath, his heart pounding loudly in his ears. Near the centre of the room, Minister Zwingli sighed before he raised his flute. “To Empress Consort Rose,” he stated, loudly. The Margraves and Counts who were acquaintances of Arthur’s father raised theirs next, and the movement spread to the corners of the room in a ripple. “To Empress Consort Rose,” they chorused and toasted. For him.

His crowning glory.

The relief that spread to his toes and the pads of his fingers was enormous. The tension in his spine snapped like a bowstring. Arthur fought the urge to flop to his knees and presented his audience a wide smile. “Thank you,” he raised his flute and nodded at the Edelweiss, the Cornflower and the Carnation, grateful for their staunch support. “Thank you very much.”

At the corner of the room, a blonde figure slinked out of the room, a thin smile etched over his gaunt face.

---

“How did it go?”

Arthur nearly jumped (the third time that evening, goodness) when he entered his chamber to find the lump beneath the blankets on his bed speaking to him. The shadows dancing beneath the candle’s dying light revealed the sickly sallow shades of the Emperor’s face as he slowly turned to face his wife.

Arthur waved a hand to dismiss his lady-in-waiting, who promptly left the room. He approached the bed carefully, unbuttoning his robes and shirt as he padded his way across. “It went well,” he reported, an eyebrow raised in puzzlement.

“Hmm,” the Emperor shrugged and turned away from him. “That’s good,” his voice was muffled by the cushions.

Arthur mulled over Emperor Francis’ strange concern as he changed into his pajamas. He told them to support me, the thought suddenly struck Arthur. The Edelweiss might not have needed persuasion to do that, but the Carnation would. The Carnation had been the flower with the second highest standing in the harem (the only flower who’d birthed an heir other than the late Empress Consort), he’d be the most compelling figure whose decisions others would follow. Not to mention that the Cornflower was expecting (a likely candidate of power in the near future).

Arthur turned and stared at the lump of shape at the other side of the bed for a long time. Gingerly, he raised his hand and placed it on top of the blanket. “You do care, don’t you?” he whispered softly.

Even breathing was his only answer.

---

Arthur had five months. Barely less than half a year of peace and support and – he was the centre of attention in the court, Prince Matthew and Prince Alfred visited twice a week, they went to the lake with the Emperor once and there was a content smile on his face, he’d shaven and showed up in luncheons and dinners, charming and graceful as they celebrated Princess Maria’s birthday, and Arthur was falling, falling in love with his husband, exchanging fond looks across the Ballroom and dining table – happiness. Pure, concentrated happiness.

The other shoe dropped. Too soon.

---

“Your Majesty.”

Arthur laid his eyes on his brother, his blood relative who had forsaken his trust on him, and nodded as they stumbled across each other’s path in the corridor. “Lord Thistle,” he greeted. The hurt lingered, but Arthur’d noticed that the shadows were disappearing from his brother’s face and he was glad, for him. “How have you been?”

Something flickered across the green irises that nearly mirrored his before James remarked, indifferently. “I’ve been fine, thank you Your Majesty.”

Arthur hated the distance that had been created between them. Baby steps, he thought to himself, he needed to take baby steps.

While Arthur debated with himself whether it was too soon to invite his brother for something, anything, to attempt to rebuild the bridge which had been burnt, James interrupted his thoughts. “Your Majesty,” there was a smile on the older begetter’s face. “Would you be free for a luncheon tomorrow?”

Arthur was ecstatic. “Gladly,” he replied almost straight away. He’d make time for his brother; others could wait.

“I’m honoured,” James gave him a quick bow, “See you at the alcove next to the library in the West Wing tomorrow at noon, Your Majesty.”

“See you,” Arthur returned with a genuine smile before they proceeded to their original destinations.

Later that night, the young Empress Consort fretted over his hopes for reconciliation as he tossed and turned in his bed. He paid no mind to the Emperor’s lack of presence in the room (although Francis had spent a lot of time with Arthur lately, he’d spent some nights with other flowers in the harem, too). Arthur nearly woke up too late and fretted again over whether he should wear what he used to wear before he was Francis’ wife (would James see it as an insult? But overdressing would exert his status and Arthur didn’t want that).

Subsequently, Arthur reached the alcove nearly half an hour late. “I’m sorry,” the Empress Consort nearly huffed and puffed as he stepped into the cozy little cranny where he used to spent hours playing chess against his brother. The round wooden table had been transformed to a mini dining table.

“It’s all right,” James reassured him from one of the chairs around the table. To Arthur’s surprise, Emperor Francis was present at James’ side. Judging from the blue-eyed blonde’s expression, the Emperor was taken aback by his Empress’ arrival, too. “Thistle,” Arthur blinked as disbelief turned to dread in the Emperor’s eyes. Aversion overwhelmed the lines of his face and his tone as the Emperor spoke, “I don’t want hi-”

“Now, now, Francis,” James interrupted with an unnatural smile on his face, his wrist pinning their sovereign’s hand against on the table in an iron grip and while large fingers caressed his knuckles affectionately in a contradiction. “Don’t worry, things would go according to plan.” There was something terribly off about his tone.

Something was really, really wrong. “What is happening?” Arthur took half a step back reflexively.

“I wouldn’t want to move away, if I were you,” James spoke coldly, a throwing knife pointed at his brother’s chest. The Thistle’s stare was downright murderous, the malice chilling Arthur to the bone, freezing his foot to the ground. “Come closer,” James beckoned, his gaze threatening. “Sit opposite to me.” The narrow space of the alcove ensured that the siblings were but a couple of yards apart, and if there was anyone who could aim better than Arthur at archery, it’s his eldest brother James. Arthur had no doubt that if James had the intention to kill him, he would die.

“Thistle,” Emperor Francis choked. “Put the knife down! Why are you involving your bro-AAAH!” his words blended into a scream when James’ fingers clamped down tightly around his hand.

His brother hated to be patronized. He wouldn’t take kindly to being told to put down his weapon. “James,” Arthur gulped as he obeyed, his feet bringing him closer to danger despite the blaring signs in his head and the adrenaline coursing in his blood, telling him to stay the hell out or knock his brother’s teeth. His voice sounded faint to his own ears. “What are you doing?” Arthur should keep calm and attempt to distract him carefully. “What are you planning to do?”

The grin that split James’ face to two looked insane. “This,” he said.

And he plunged the blade into Emperor Francis’ chest.

“…My apologies,” Alfred fought the urge to gulp and forced his lips to curl upwards, facial muscles contorting to a polite, amicable expression. “I’m surprised. I didn’t think Terra-sama would be so majestic. I’m rendered speechless by your radiance.”

The blonde Deity’s left eye twitched, and Alfred wondered if he’d stuck his foot to his mouth.

“Thank you,” Terra voiced, and Alfred almost let out the breath he’d been holding when his ‘husband’ added, “Your boorishness astounds me, too, handsome lad.”

A vein popped on Alfred’s temple. T-this…tranny, he seethed inwardly.

“Me thinks,” sweet, beautiful Bess spoke, a finger pressed on her chin in a pondering posture (oh my God, she’s so cute, why, oh WHY- Alfred thought), “We should move somewhere more comfortable for this kind of activity.” The way she said the last word implied a myriad of things Alfred didn’t want to imagine. He shuddered.

Brunei and Seychelles peered at the God they served and waited for his cue.

“…Alright,” The green-eyed male finally sighed. “I need tea, anyways.”

Alfred, though, needed something way stronger.

Groom of the Mountain Deity

Chapter 2

 

“OOOHH!” Something pink, flashy and frilly assaulted Alfred as soon as he entered the oriental-style living room. “Isn’t he, like, so cute? Like, so handsome? I completely like you!” [1]

Alfred could only blink at the petite blonde that had grabbed his hand and launched himself onto Alfred’s lap. If he thought Terra was a transsexual before, this one was definitely more…extreme. Terra wore muted colours and voluminous, androgynous robes. This male wore fabrics that clung to his lack of curves and dangly gold accessories in his hair.

“Feliks!” a brown-haired, blue-eyed, normally dressed male (thank goodness!) pried the pouting blonde away from Alfred and bowed in apology. “I’m so sorry, Feliks is always like that, please understand him.” He smiled friendlily at Alfred, and Alfred automatically felt that this brunet could be a valuable friend in this freaking huge castle of weirdos. “I’m Toris. Others often refer to me as Lithuania, that’s the spring I’m guarding.”

“I’m Alfred,” the human introduced himself, “from the village at the foot of the mountain. The spring has been our important source of water,” he stated gratefully.

“I’m Feliks. I’m a sprite of fire,” Feliks butted in, leaned on Toris’ back and offered his hand. Alfred took it hesitantly, mentally cringing when Feliks shook his hand enthusiastically. The sprite’s hand was, expectedly, warm to the touch. “Nice to meet you!” Feliks grinned.

“Poland, please keep your volume down,” the words were spoken in an even, baritone voice from the other corner of the room. Alfred looked up to find a dark-haired man walking to the table at the centre with a tray filled with teapot and empty cups, an ivory and crimson oriental robe covering his lean frame. Two white triangular appendices stood out from his head and a white, bushy, fluffy tail sprouting from his behind swished in the air as he bent down to place the tray atop the ornate table cloth.

Alfred’s eyes widened. A fox spirit? This was the first time he saw one!

Meanwhile, the fox poured the tea to a cup and presented it to Terra, who’d taken a seat on one of the sofas, with Bess sitting next to him, leaning on his side. “Thank you, Kiku,” gratitude was apparent in Terra’s voice as he took the cup from the fox’s hands. “The tea you brew is always the best.”

Patches of pink appeared on the fox’s pale cheeks. “You’re exaggerating, Terra-san.”

If Alfred noticed that the two held the cup together and stared at each other a tad too long, he dismissed this observation.

“Lad,” Terra gave him a look and gestured at the sofa across the table. “Sit down.”

The Deity’s attitude was seriously pissing Alfred off.

Toris seemed to notice the blue-eyed blonde’s irritation. He pressed his hand to the small of Alfred’s back briefly as he guided the human to the sofa. “Please make yourself at home,” he smiled.

The fox served him tea and cookies as soon as he sat down and the moment he took a bite, he couldn’t control himself. He didn’t realise how hungry he was until this…sweet, sugary, exquisite goodness was presented to him. How long was he in the river? Alfred thought vaguely as he inhaled his food.

When Alfred paused to fill his throat with tea, he caught the disdain on Terra’s face, the crease between his massive brows, the sneer on his lips, the tilt of his chin and how he looked down at him, at the fecking lowly human sitting opposite him. Half of Alfred was embarrassed that he was not in his best behaviour in front of the Deity and afraid that if he was found wanting Terra wouldn’t relieve his village of the drought. The other half was angry, indignant and defensive. His day had been sucky and he wasn’t welcome here why on earth is he here-

“Why are you so uncivilized?” the other shoe finally dropped. Terra clucked his tongue in disapproval. “Has your mother never taught you any manners? What kind of a woman was sh-”

Alfred shot up to his feet and smacked his palms on the surface of the table so hard the cups jumped to the air before falling off the table and crashed on the ground, or they were knocked sideways, tea seeping onto the table cloth. “DON’T INSULT MY MOM!” He yelled. “She died when I was little, I grew up with my brother so sorry if I don’t have any manners, Your Grace!” he sneered sarcastically.

The room was silent. Everyone watched the human with wide eyes.

Shit. Alfred cursed when he realised what he’d done. Shit. I’ve yelled at Terra-sama. I’ve yelled at a DEITY. SHI-

 “I think you’re, like, tired, Alfred,” Feliks flung his hands around Alfred’s arms suddenly, “Let’s get you somewhere you can sleep! Liet, go with me!” He dragged the human away from the sofa (he’s surprisingly strong, stronger than me, even, Alfred thought before he berated himself, of course he’s strong, he’s not human) and pulled him across the room. “We’ll make him presentable for you tonight!” Feliks shouted over his shoulder at Terra as Lithuania scrambled to his feet to follow the other spiritual being.

Tonight. Alfred thought of the implication of the word, and his stomach churned. He didn’t want to think about it.

---

As soon as the trio left, Bess turned to her companion and sighed. “Don’t be too mean to him,” she advised him.

“Don’t patronise me,” the Deity remarked coldly, though his expression was tinged by guilt. “I don’t want him here. That’s the point.”

“It must be hard for Alfred-san, to be separated from his brother,” Kiku commented as he cleared the table, the porcelain clinking softly as he arranged the cups back on his tray. “To be honest, isn’t this the same as being cast away by his neighbours and his society?” [2]

Terra stared at the pieces of shattered porcelain on the ground (his poor, prized tea set), before he closed his eyes and sighed. “I’m taking a bath,” Brunei tended to him as soon as he rose to his feet.

“Don’t forget to drop him a visit,” Bess spoke to Terra’s retreating back.

Alfred loved his room.

The mattress was unbelievably soft and springy. The cotton of the sheet and his new pajama was cool against his skin. Soothing scent of lavender and mint suffused the room from the burner inside a lion-shaped ceramic figurine. Luxurious items he’d never even seen before in his life filled the spacious room to the brim, from the furniture, the linens, the décor, the clothes inside the closet…

If only Matthew was here.

The door was knocked, and Alfred was snapped out of his reverie. His feet slipped into his new sandals (made of the smoothest rattan he’d ever come to know, light and comfortable) before he stood and opened the door. “What’s up-”

Terra stood in the corridor, a tray with two mugs held in his hands. The Deity had changed into a piece of navy blue nightgown that went slight past his knees, showing his pale, leanly muscular calves and delicate ankles. All the gold and gems that adorned his coarse blonde locks had been taken off. “I’m bringing you warm milk,” his voice was soft as a whisper, his eyes almost luminous in the dimness of the night.

Alfred tensed (come to think of it, tonight is his wedding night, isn’t it? But Terra wasn’t involved in the ceremony at all! Of course, the highly inaccurate statue had been involved in the ceremony his village held, but did that count? Can Alfred have sex with a male? Screw having sex with males, Alfred is a virgin! Nobody wanted to have sex with the village freak. Oh, no, what should he do-) before he let the Deity into his room and sat on his bed stiffly, the line of his spine and his limbs stiff as a rod.

Terra chose to sit on the wooden chair next to the nightstand he’d put the tray on. “Kiku has added honey to it,” Terra picked up one of the mug and opened the lid, letting the steam out to the breezy night air. He blew on the surface daintily, thin lips puckering against the rim of the porcelain. The light of the candle cast shadows on his pale skin, mystifying his face and making his brows less prominent. Alfred watched as Terra took a gulp and moaned softly. “Hmmm…it’s good,” he gestured at the other mug when he put his mug down and wiped the white ring around his lips. “You should try it.”

“Y-yes,” Alfred followed the procedure at the blink of an eye; he was a bundle of nerves confused at the heat pooling in his abdomen and the vague feeling of…arousal (b-but they’re both MALES!!) and succeeded to scald his tongue. “Bwah!” he almost spat the milk back to the mug and dropped the mug to his bed. Droplets of milk dripped down his chin and stained his pajama instead.

His cheeks burned at his clumsiness when he heard Terra’s laughter. “Don’t laugh at me!” He turned to the God and puffed his cheeks.

“B-but, you’re so…childlike,” Terra managed between gasps and bouts of chuckles, his chest heaving as he took out a handkerchief from his pocket and dabbed his face. When Terra laughed, his whole face laughed with him it seemed, the lines of his lips and cheeks and eyes curving upwards as splotches of pink spread across his face. And his eyes, his eyes were brighter than gems, lively and radiant (and amused). The residue of a smile eliminated any harshness to his face (including the massiveness of his brows) and made it relaxed, soft, welcoming.

Beautiful.

Alfred stared in fascination. His face turned so red he feared that his blood vessels had burst. He supposed he was thankful he had the embarrassment as an excuse.

When Terra’s laughter dissipated and his facial expression was calm again (Alfred nearly lamented the loss), seriousness entered his eyes. “Lad, I come here to apologise,” he revealed the purpose of his visit as he leaned back on the chair, “about what I said about your mother.”

Alfred couldn’t decide whether he should be relieved or disappointed. His mind (his heart, and his libido, too) was puzzling him. “It’s all right,” he replied instead. “Apology accepted.” He grinned. “Thanks for the milk, by the way.” He blew at the surface longer and sipped more cautiously this time. “You’re right! It’s delicious!”

Terra merely shook his head at the human’s antique before reaching for his milk again. It’s good that Alfred had relaxed at least; he’d been so tense before. Terra remembered what Bess and Kiku had told him and asked, “Do you miss home? Do you miss your brother and your friends?”

The human replied straight away. “No,” he grinned, “it’s only been a day, how can I be homesick?”

“Really…?” Terra watched Alfred’s eyes astutely before he turned his head and stared over the window. What a reckless chap, Terra thought silently, not really self-aware, isn’t he.

Are you asking me this because you’re going to send me home? Alfred thought as he stared at Terra’s quiet figure. You can’t send me home without blessing our land. Besides, I have no friends.

The two sat in tranquility for a while, before the clouds over the windows parted and the moon showed itself, round and white like a huge pearl hung on the velvety dark blue sky. Terra turned to the human to tell him about it to find the tall, muscular, blonde country hick (he really was a country hick. Did the villagers want to be cursed for sending him this…this unrefined puppy?) deeply asleep, light snores escaping his parted mouth.

Terra watched the vermilion flame on the candle as the hour of the Boar turned the hour of the Rat [3]. On the wall opposite to the window, the silhouette cast by the moonlight morphed, the height of the figure shrinking, harsh, flat planes filling out to soft, rounded (albeit muted) curves, broad shoulders and lanky limbs narrowing slightly. In the place of the God now sat a petite woman, her chin leaning on her hand as she observed the blonde man sleeping across her. [4]

In Alfred’s dream, Alfred sees blue, luxuries and beautiful women. Alfred sees the gentle curve of a person’s lips. Alfred sees concerned dark violet eyes, soft blonde waves framing a face that was almost his mirror-image. Alfred sees a pair of gloved hands, reaching out to him as the villagers pushed him over the cliff, sacrificed him to their God-

“…Matthew,” Alfred murmured, calling for his twin unconsciously, missing the person he’d never been parted with since birth. Beads of tears leaked out of his eyes and slid down the curve of his cheeks.

The Goddess on the chair next to the nightstand moved to the bed and bent over the human, gentle fingers erasing his tears and stroking his hair. Her own hair fell over his face and shoulder, long, straight strands of sandy-coloured locks, sturdy and thick as stalks of wheat.

“You are a liar, lad,” she murmured softly, round green eyes under thick, long lashes watching over the boy in the bed.

Alfred smells wheat, berries and wild petunias, the scent of harvest and the forest outside the village, where he plays with his twin and an odd white-haired brother, running and laughing and having fun.

Alfred smiles.

“Mister…”


“Uuugghhhh…” Alfred rolled onto his stomach.


“Mister!”


“Mmrrrhh….Five more minutes, please, Matt…” he batted at the source of disturbance.


“Let me handle him-”


Ah. Matt had left him alone. Awesome.


“Sey-“


“OOI, OOI, OPEN YOUR EYES!” Something grabbed his collar and shook his body so hard his teeth clacked.


“Whaa-?” Alfred woke up with a jolt, disoriented eyes blinking at the two faces hovering above him.


And such lovely faces they were, long inky lashes framing dark chocolate irises, cute button noses and rosy lips adorning smooth bronze skin. The girl further from him had golden scarves covering her head and the upper half of her long ivory and silver dress, colourful breads handing from the seams of her sleeves, round eyes peering at him shyly. The one holding him had her long black wavy hair in two ponytails and her lean arms out in the open air brazenly, almond-shaped eyes glaring at him. “About bloody time!” she clucked her tongue.


 “...Have I died and gone to heaven?” Alfred murmured dreamily, his eyes never leaving the two richly dressed gorgeous females. They were so…exotic. So different from the fair skinned, fair haired village folks.


The girl with two ponytails snorted, “You wish.” She let go of him and he fell to his hands and knees.


“Ouch…” Alfred rose to his feet and dusted his clothes, checking for any wounds on his being. His heart beat strongly under his ribcages, and Alfred let out a breath he didn’t realise he was holding before he continued his inspection. He still had the velvety robe with him, but all other delicate fineries were gone, washed away by the torrents of the river. He briefly lamented their loss before the tomboyish girl hollered, “OOI! Get your lazy arse here, worthless human!”


“Seychelles…” the shyer girl sighed.


“Coming!” Alfred looked up to follow the sound of their fading footsteps. And he gasped.


Groom of the Mountain Deity

Chapter 1


There was a castle in front of him.


A HUGE fecking castle, erected on the clouds floating above the hills.


A long flight of staircase led them from the shore of the lake he was washed towards to the grand fortress, odd-looking features such as swirling bulbs and oriental bamboo-like rooftops attached to the chambers, breezy corridors and bridges connecting the wings to the main building. The extensive garden was filled by colourful bushes of beautiful flowers and majestic statues which looked like tiny gems from where Alfred was standing.


And it was rather dazzling, to a country bumpkin like Alfred, whose village chief did not even live in a three-storey mansion with potted plants in his garden. To think of it, his village was rather poor.


“Careful, your jaw may drop,” the tomboy smirked at him when he managed to catch up to them, his feet taking a mind on their own.


Alfred closed and opened his mouth several times, blue eyes wide, as he turned to the two petite females and finally managed to ask. “…Is one of you our Deity, Terra?”


The smirk fell from the tomboy’s face. “…What do you think?” The two stared at him expressionlessly, the sudden indifference throwing Alfred off guard and causing dread to fill his stomach. “What have you humans circulated about Terra?”


Alfred gulped. “That…”


“Kiddo.”


Alfred turned from the fishing pole he’d been watching over, one hand covering his eyes from the glaring sun. He spotted the red-eyed albino who’d been his twin’s buddy for years, fellow freaks of the village whom he’d come to see as his own older brother. “Oh, hey, Gilbert!”


“…I heard.” The albino’s expression was so grave Alfred knew that he did, before the words left his lips.


“Oh. Well,” Alfred turned back to his attempt to catch dinner. “No need to thank the awesome me! Hahah-”


“Listen, kiddo,” the albino had his grip around the collar of Alfred’s tattered shirt. “…Terra is a ruthless Deity. Don’t ever anger Her. She will rip your soul and eat your flesh. I’m not joking.”


There was no shit-eating grin on the albino’s face. He wasn’t joking.


He found that he was unable to continue. “…Umm…uh…”


The tomboy’s dainty lips curled leftwards, the grin shattering the tension of the moment. “We’re only two of Terra’s minions.” She tossed her hair back and turned to climb up the stairs. “But whatever you humans gossip about, I’m sure most of the bad ones are true.”


“Seychelles,” the shyer one sighed before sparing him an apologetic glance as they followed her. “Don’t be afraid,” her voice was as soft as a breath. “Terra is gracious.”


He wished. Oh, boy, he wished.


*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*-*

After going through corridors and hallways of breathtaking décor, gold plated railings, pastel-coloured wallpaper, crystalline lamps and peculiar, gleaming pieces of furniture lying around one corner or another, Alfred’s exotic guides dumped him to one of the pavilions in the garden. “Wait here!” the tomboy, who’s introduced herself as Seychelles, ordered him with her hands on her waist. The discreet one, Brunei [1], gave her partner a patronizing stare. “We’ll inform Terra that the humans have sent another groom.”


The tone in which she spoke the word made Alfred shudder. Was Terra really a man-eating Deity?? Before he could voice his inquiry, the two spritely ladies were gone.


Alfred sat on the comfortably padded wooden bench inside the pavilion. And waited.


But out of the seven virtues of a hero (or any other human beings, really), patience was a virtue he really didn’t possess. Temperance, too, but that’s neither here nor there. Yet.


Anyways. After five minutes of staring at the patterns of mythical animals crafted on the iron railings of the pavilion, Alfred couldn’t stand it anymore. He stepped away from the pavilion to inspect one of the marble statues he’d spied as he walked up the never-ending staircase. “I won’t go far,” he thought absently as he meandered through the bushes, “I’ll go back as soon I see anyone approa-aaaAAAAHHH”


Alfred screamed. One moment he was walking, the next, he’d lost his footing and he was plummeting to the ground at such a neck-breaking speed. Technically, Alfred knew the castle and the gardens are built on clouds, but he didn’t realise that the edge of the clouds would be so freaking near. Layers and levels of gardens and buildings flashed across his sight, blue, green and brick red passing by dizzyingly as he thought, No, not again, I’m too young to die-


SPLASH!


Alfred hit the surface of the water headfirst and went under, blue eyes blinking at the wavering weeds and flowering plants at the bottom, waving as the clear, soothing water were shaken by his movements, the crimson of the petals shocking as blood. Alfred watched the spider lilies furling and unfurling, fishes of different sizes and shapes swimming by, sunlight distorted by the ripples of the water above his head reflected in fine, silvery scales, before Alfred swam upwards easily, wet fringe dripping water in rivulets as he waddled.


And saw red, waving in the wind, locks of wavy hair rich as the orb of sunset, bleeding vermilion to the golden canvas of the horizon.


Alfred stared at the owner of such gorgeous, bold hair in fascination, a hazel-eyed woman with strong, majestic facial features, long lashes casting shadow on high cheekbones, ivory and maroon fabric swathing long, lean legs. A piece of bronze breastplate covered her broad-shouldered, curvaceous torso over her shirt, the figure of a phoenix carved on the metal and the sheath covering the sword slung over her back. She was otherworldly, ethereal – her very figure emanated power, grace and beauty. She looked like a Goddess.


“Oh, dear!” she noticed him when he sunk underwater again (he’d been floating without moving his limbs, too entranced by the sight he’s drinking in like a dying man in a desert) and spluttered as water entered his nasal passages. Strong hands pulled him when he drifted ashore, and helped him as he climbed the banks, crunching water lilies and tall grasses on his wake. “Are you all right?” her voice was pleasant to the ears, the texture of her fingers smooth as silk. Alfred stared as her red, luscious lips moved around the words.


If this is the Deity I’m married to, the very thought made Alfred’s throat dry. I don’t mind being consumed by her. “I-I a-am fine,” he stuttered and blushed, “t-thank you!”


Those piercing hazel eyes inspected him closely. Alfred watched the specks of green surrounding her round, dark pupils, flickering as she blinked. “…You’re...human, are you?”


Yes…and I’ll be your husband, Alfred nearly spoke, before a loud, deafening yell interrupted them. “SO THERE YOU ARE!!”

Alfred blinked and turned to see his ponytailed guide, Seychelles, fuming at him as she pointed an accusing finger at him. The blue-eyed blonde flustered in embarrassment as she jogged to the two of them in a flurry of fabrics. “Where have you been? I told you to stay put!!” She crossed her arms and scolded him. “You’ve made Terra wait! That’s terribly rude!”


“I’m sorry,” Alfred mumbled and shuffled his feet. Oh God, first meeting with his wife of a Deity and he’d inconvenienced her. What a bad impression.


“You don’t need to be so uptight, Seychelles.” The gorgeous redhead chuckled and Alfred peered at her in wonder. She shot him a smile and Alfred blushed from being caught sneaking glances. “Put the guy at ease, won’t you?”


Such a generous Goddess, Alfred thought, Oh my, am I not lucky.


Seychelles frowned. “But-”


“Seychelles,” someone called softly, shadows of two figures slipping into the periphery of Alfred’s sight. The redhead looked ahead and dropped to her knees all of a sudden. “Terra,” she breathed before bowing her head, letting tresses of vermillion curls form a curtain around her head.


Alfred’s thoughts screeched to a halt. Wait, what?


Seychelles whipped around and took a sharp breath before her hand reached out to grab Alfred’s wrist and yanked. Hard. Alfred fell to his knees as she kowtowed at the drop of a hat. “Your Grace,” Seychelles greeted, and Alfred followed her stance, his mind reeling. What’s going on isn’t the redhead Terra oh she isn’t is she-


“Please rise,” the voice that spoke the words was husky and melodious, the lilt to the accent soothing. There was fondness and exasperation in the statement that followed. “Bess, you know better than to be that formal with me.”


The redhead chuckled as she rose to her feet. “You know I like to tease you, Terra.”


‘Bess’…she wasn’t Terra, Alfred was still processing that discovery with something akin to disappointment in his head when Seychelles nudged him. He scrambled to his feet and looked up hesitantly. Here goes-


The sight that greeted Alfred was nothing short of breathtaking. If he’d thought Bess’ eyes were gorgeous, Terra’s were gems, pure leaf green irises staring at him with such intensity and strength. Ivory and jade green robes swathed her lean figure, patterns of roses sewn on the hems with golden and maroon threads, contrasting starkly against the pink, pale skin that glided over the pronounced, delicate bones structure of her collar. Chains of gold and riches adorned the graceful line of her neck, earrings of gold rubies and emeralds swaying against the curve of a defined jaw. When Terra shifted, the line of her robes revealed more of her slim, muscled calves, smooth as a baby’s cheeks and unmarred.


There were just a few...anomalies.


First, the eyebrows. Oh my, they’re damn bushy.


Next, the hair. Horribly short, choppy and mused, unsexy kind of bedraggled. And those sandy blonde strands didn’t look soft to the touch.


Last, and most importantly. A lack of curves.


Alfred watched as those eyebrows he’d been gawking at furrowed and those thin, pink, damn kissable lips turned down in a vicious scowl. “What are you looking at?” Terra barked, low, scratchy and so obviously masculine and Alfred nearly stepped back in horrification. Oh. My. God.


I’m married to a guy.

America fears England sometimes.


The lankier nation hovers above him as he thrust into him at a rhythm that makes his knees weak and turns his brain to mush, his hands holding him down against the mattress (even when America reaches out to wound his arms around England’s neck). Green eyes darken and gleam, fix themselves on him as swollen lips curl to the left, feverish and prideful and-


That’s not lust, America thinks hazily, and that’s not affection, either. That’s the look someone gives his trophy at his cabinet, he realizes.


England’s nails dig into the flesh around his heart, and America shudders.

“Sometimes I don’t like the way you hold onto me.”


America gives England the benefit of the doubt.


England curls around America in the bed of his hotel room, the curve of his spine arched in lethargy like a cat’s. It’s their umpteenth post-conference accident this year. They no longer need the excuse of alcohol and violence and America likes it.


“What, just now?” America hears England’s question.


“During. And after.” America curls up on top of the pillow, cheeks bunching like a child’s as he pouts. “It’s kind of creepy. Like you’re not looking at me me at all.”


“At you you,” scoffs England. “Are you trying to be bloody difficult?”


America shakes his head inwardly, unsure of how he should interpret England’s responses. Is he defensive? Is he exasperated at America’s supposed idiocy? America hopes his notions of fear are just that, a mere idiocy. “And you should cut your nails. Fucking stings.” He tries again.


England did not respond verbally.


Fingers search and rub the indents of crescent marks on America’s skin.


The arms around his waist tighten.

It starts with America’s provocation.


Everyone veers off England’s periphery when he’s under the influence of alcohol. That’s common sense. But America likes to challenge conventions. He watches in fascination the transitions of England’s ‘I-want-to-get-naked drunk’ to ‘weepy drunk’ state, before he ends as a ‘violent drunk’.  They hurl their fists and words at each other, words so nasty they would regret ever mentioning, before England touches his damp cheeks (when did he begin to cry?) with his fingers and lips and they tumble into bed and America thinks, fucking finally.


The next world conference, America sticks around England. Well, they’ve fucked, so that counts for something, right? And England’s one of his few friends, he has to make sure that things don’t get awkward, right? At the end of the day, England snaps at him – he’s hot like that, America thinks – and they have glorious sex. Multiple glorious ones.


The rest, well, is history.


‘Why?’ England starts looking at him with that question one fine night, when America happily drips water onto the carpet of England’s hotel room from his towels as he exits the shower, warm steam curling against his skin pleasantly. The question is apparent in his persistent stare, loud in the silence.


America falters at the gaze he feels on his back before he turns to his former caretaker, studies his guarded expression – he’s not giving any clues, it’s too soon to lay everything on the table – and merely beams.


Later, when they’re cuddling in bed and England’s even breathing lulls America to sleep, he drops a kiss on his forehead and murmurs, “Sometimes I can’t wait to see you again, old man, even if you’re kinda still like a jerk.”

---

America is angry at England.


He tugs at his collar as he ignores the elder’s advices on his presentation delivery and negotiation techniques. The hickey on his neck burns when the starch of his shirt brushes his skin and he frowns irately. He doesn’t like to be marked. He’s told England more times than his hands could count.


From the corner of his eye, America sees England approaching him after spotting him from the end of the corridor, his pursed lips brimming with more indignant words. America seethes inwardly, steps closer to Israel, and throws any sense of propriety out of the window in his interaction with the other nation.


Later, as the conference proceeds and America exaggerates his obnoxious ways, America spies England looking down on his lap, his lips downturned and the lines of his face tense and unhappy and- please don’t be upset.


America does not apologise.

---

England is trying something.


For once, England accommodates to his whims. He buys America dinner, does not interrupt America (too much) when he shares his stories and brilliant ideas, kisses America without mentioning that taboo of a word. The first few days, America stares at the island nation with suspicion in his eyes. But England stills sputters and lectures him when America provokes him, sharp tongue prattling with a steady supply of sarcasm. Fortunately, the frequency is sparse, and anyways, England wouldn’t be England without his criticisms.


For two weeks, America’s in heaven. Nothing could go wrong in the little piece of heaven he– England and him, he corrected – have carved out on earth. America’s ecstatic. He laughs a lot and lets England cling to him and hold him however he pleases.


If only I can live the rest of my life like this, America wishes.


In his head, he plans for a date in a theatre or a museum, to accommodate England, for once, and grins.


(Sometimes, America catches England staring at him with a tiny frown on his face and hopes he’s not found wanting. He doesn’t want the other shoe to drop yet, not when nothing has begun.)

---

“England,” America moans his name reverently, hanging onto it like it’s a mantra, “England, there, that’s it, that’s—”


“Shut up,” England cards his fingers through America’s hair and yanks his head back. America feels the edges of England’s teeth pressing lightly against the skin of his throat and nearly protests before England’s lips slide to his jaws, the muscles of his lean abdomen pressing America’s erection closer to his own stomach and keeps it there, trapped against skin and heat. The friction drives America wild.


“Nnk! Uh! O-oh fuck, fuck—”


England pulls the strands of hair held between his fingers tightly and America winces. England’s fixated stare starts making him uncomfortable, dark and brimming with pride and paranoia. It reminds him of centuries past, of confident, demanding, conforming gazes that stripped him off any shred of freedom. America hates it.


“England,” America gasps, twists and looks at the nation above him, looks at him imploringly, channeling all his emotions for his former caretaker into the connection between their eyes. I love you, let me be your equal, don’t go back to the past, isn’t it so much better now?


England takes a shuddering breath, buries into him deeply and cries against his shoulder.


America’s heart sinks.

---

“What the hell!?”


It’s the first thing America shouts at England’s face the next time they see each other.


“Why have you been avoiding me?” He grabs England’s wrist before the other nation could escape and drags him along the corridor till he finds the nearest empty room. He pushes England inside and corners him against the wall. “You haven’t been answering my emails. When I call you in your office your secretary always directs me to your aide and your operator tells me your number is no longer available! What the hell, England!? How could you just up and leave without saying anything!!” he yells emotionally, his chest heaving with his breath. I thought I matter to you. I thought we’re…something.


“I want out,” England shrugs and bows his head. “I think the message is clear.”


America flinches and squeezes England’s shoulders as he presses him closer to the wall. “Why?” He croaks, uncaring of the blatant display of weakness on his face. The scenario he’s prepped himself for does not materialise. He intends to confront England coldly. He cannot. “Why is it so sudden? Was it something I did?” I thought you care about me. “I…” America licks his lip nervously, “I want to be with you.” He finally, finally bares his heart.


England continues to stay silent and looks down at his shoes.


America swallows the bitterness that clogs his throat and takes a step back. “If…” he hates the sound of his voice, the sheer pitifulness, “if you don’t love me, then I understand-”


“I do love you,” England interrupts, softly.


America stares at England hopefully. “Then-”


“I don’t think I love you the way you want me to,” England ploughs on. “I love you like I want to keep you on a shelf, and never let you see anyone else but me. I love you so much I want you to be mine, mine alone,” he speaks to his shoes before he looks up and stares right into America’s eyes. “This is for your own good. And mine.”


America is stunned.


But he is not surprised that he is not surprised.


Somewhere, subconsciously, he’s known.

---
